22. Difference between splice , slice and substring?
    
    ## ðŸ§  Quick Comparison Table

    | Method       | Works On     | Mutates Original? | Returns         | Use Case                          |
    |--------------|--------------|-------------------|------------------|-----------------------------------|
    | `slice()`    | Arrays & Strings | âŒ No          | New array or string | Extract without changing original |
    | `splice()`   | Arrays only     | âœ… Yes         | Removed items (array) | Add/remove items from array       |
    | `substring()`| Strings only    | âŒ No          | New string         | Extract part of a string          |

    ---

    ## ðŸ” `slice()` â€“ Non-Destructive Extractor

    ### âœ… Works on: Arrays & Strings  
    ### âŒ Does NOT modify original  
    ### ðŸ“¦ Returns: A new array or string

    ```js
    const arr = [1, 2, 3, 4, 5];
    console.log(arr.slice(1, 4)); // [2, 3, 4]
    console.log(arr);            // [1, 2, 3, 4, 5] (unchanged)

    const str = "JavaScript";
    console.log(str.slice(4, 10)); // "Script"
    ```

    ---

    ## ðŸ”§ `splice()` â€“ Destructive Modifier (Arrays Only)

    ### âœ… Works on: Arrays  
    ### âœ… Modifies original array  
    ### ðŸ“¦ Returns: Removed elements

    ```js
    const arr = [1, 2, 3, 4, 5];
    const removed = arr.splice(2, 2); // Remove 2 items starting at index 2
    console.log(removed); // [3, 4]
    console.log(arr);     // [1, 2, 5] (modified)
    ```

    You can also **insert** items:
    ```js
    arr.splice(1, 0, "a", "b"); // Insert at index 1
    console.log(arr); // [1, "a", "b", 2, 5]
    ```

    ---

    ## âœ‚ï¸ `substring()` â€“ String Extractor

    ### âœ… Works on: Strings only  
    ### âŒ Does NOT modify original  
    ### ðŸ“¦ Returns: New string

    ```js
    const str = "JavaScript";
    console.log(str.substring(4, 10)); // "Script"
    ```

    ðŸ”¸ Difference from `slice()`:
    - `substring()` swaps indices if `start > end`
    - `slice()` does not

    ```js
    str.slice(10, 4);      // "" (empty string)
    str.substring(10, 4);  // "Script" (swaps indices)
    ```

    ---

    ## ðŸ§  Interview-Ready Summary

    > "`slice()` and `substring()` are non-mutating methods for extracting parts of arrays or strings. `splice()` is array-specific and modifies the original arrayâ€”great for adding or removing items. Understanding their differences is key to writing clean, predictable code."





23. Shift and Unshift?
    

    ## ðŸ”„ `shift()` â€“ Remove First Element

    - Removes the **first element** of an array
    - **Mutates** the original array
    - Returns the removed element

    ### ðŸ§ª Example:
    ```js
    const arr = [10, 20, 30];
    const first = arr.shift();

    console.log(first); // 10
    console.log(arr);   // [20, 30]
    ```

    ---

    ## âž• `unshift()` â€“ Add to Beginning

    - Adds one or more elements to the **start** of an array
    - **Mutates** the original array
    - Returns the **new length** of the array

    ### ðŸ§ª Example:
    ```js
    const arr = [20, 30];
    const newLength = arr.unshift(5, 10);

    console.log(newLength); // 4
    console.log(arr);       // [5, 10, 20, 30]
    ```

    ---

    ## ðŸ§  Interview-Ready Summary

    > "`shift()` removes the first item from an array and returns it, while `unshift()` adds items to the beginning and returns the new length. Both modify the original array and are useful when working with queues or prepending data."

24. Spread vs Rest?
    Great one, VAIBHAV! The **rest** and **spread** operators in JavaScript both use the same syntax (`...`), but they serve **opposite purposes** depending on context. Letâ€™s break it down clearly so you can explain it like a pro in interviews and use it confidently in your code.

    ---

    ## ðŸ”„ Syntax: `...` (Three Dots)

    Same symbol, **two different roles**:

    | Operator     | Purpose                        | Context Used In         |
    |--------------|--------------------------------|--------------------------|
    | `rest`       | **Collects** multiple values into one | Function parameters, destructuring |
    | `spread`     | **Expands** one value into multiple | Function calls, array/object literals |

    ---

    ## ðŸ§³ Rest Operator â€“ "Pack It Up"

    ### âœ… Used to **gather** remaining values into an array or object

    ### ðŸ“¦ Function Parameters
    ```js
    function sum(...numbers) {
    return numbers.reduce((a, b) => a + b, 0);
    }

    sum(1, 2, 3); // 6
    ```

    ### ðŸ“¦ Array Destructuring
    ```js
    const [first, ...rest] = [10, 20, 30, 40];
    console.log(first); // 10
    console.log(rest);  // [20, 30, 40]
    ```

    ### ðŸ“¦ Object Destructuring
    ```js
    const { name, ...details } = { name: "Vaibhav", age: 25, city: "Rae Bareli" };
    console.log(details); // { age: 25, city: "Rae Bareli" }
    ```

    ---

    ## ðŸŽ¯ Spread Operator â€“ "Break It Out"

    ### âœ… Used to **expand** arrays or objects into individual elements

    ### ðŸ“¦ Function Calls
    ```js
    const nums = [1, 2, 3];
    Math.max(...nums); // 3
    ```

    ### ðŸ“¦ Array Literals
    ```js
    const arr1 = [1, 2];
    const arr2 = [...arr1, 3, 4];
    console.log(arr2); // [1, 2, 3, 4]
    ```

    ### ðŸ“¦ Object Literals
    ```js
    const base = { a: 1, b: 2 };
    const extended = { ...base, c: 3 };
    console.log(extended); // { a: 1, b: 2, c: 3 }
    ```

    ---

    ## ðŸ§  Interview-Ready Summary

    > "`rest` collects multiple values into a single variableâ€”great for flexible function arguments and destructuring. `spread` expands valuesâ€”perfect for copying, merging, or passing elements individually. They use the same syntax but serve opposite roles depending on context."

25. Execution Context?
